{
  "Coronary artery disease is caused primarily by:": "",
  "Valve disease only": "",
  "Atherosclerosis (plaque buildup) in the coronary arteries": "",
  "Genetics alone": "",
  "Viral infection of the heart": "",
  "Coronary artery disease develops when atherosclerotic plaques composed of cholesterol, fat, calcium, and inflammatory cells accumulate in the coronary artery walls, progressively narrowing the lumen and restricting blood flow to the myocardium.": "",
  "A myocardial infarction (heart attack) occurs when:": "",
  "Blood pressure drops suddenly": "",
  "Heart valves fail to close properly": "",
  "The heart beats too slowly": "",
  "A coronary artery is blocked, causing death of heart muscle tissue": "",
  "A myocardial infarction occurs when a coronary artery becomes completely occluded, usually by a blood clot forming on a ruptured atherosclerotic plaque, cutting off oxygen supply and causing irreversible death (necrosis) of the downstream heart muscle.": "",
  "Symptoms of a myocardial infarction typically include:": "",
  "Only leg swelling and peripheral edema caused by right-sided venous congestion and elevated hydrostatic pressure": "",
  "Only a headache and dizziness caused by temporary cerebral vasospasm and reduced blood flow to the occipital cortex": "",
  "Only mild fatigue and general malaise caused by reduced cardiac output and diminished oxygen delivery to skeletal muscles": "",
  "Chest pain or pressure, shortness of breath, sweating, nausea, and pain radiating to the arm or jaw": "",
  "Classic MI symptoms include substernal chest pain or pressure, diaphoresis, dyspnea, nausea, and radiating pain to the left arm or jaw, though presentations can be atypical, especially in women, elderly patients, and diabetics.": "",
  "Heart failure means the heart:": "",
  "Cannot pump efficiently enough to meet the body's needs": "",
  "Has a valve that is too large": "",
  "Has an arrhythmia": "",
  "Has stopped beating completely": "",
  "Heart failure is a chronic condition in which the weakened or stiffened heart cannot pump blood effectively enough to meet the body's metabolic demands, leading to fluid congestion in the lungs and/or peripheral tissues.": "",
  "Angina pectoris is:": "",
  "A heart attack causing permanent muscle death": "",
  "An infection of the heart lining": "",
  "A type of heart valve disease": "",
  "Chest pain from temporary myocardial ischemia without tissue death": "",
  "Angina pectoris is chest pain caused by temporary, reversible ischemia of the heart muscle (reduced blood flow but no cell death), often triggered by exertion or stress and relieved by rest or nitroglycerin, serving as a warning sign of underlying coronary artery disease.": "",
  "Risk factors for coronary artery disease include:": "",
  "Only a sedentary lifestyle with prolonged inactivity reducing cardiovascular fitness": "",
  "Only advanced age and the associated loss of vascular elasticity over time": "",
  "Only inherited genetic factors predisposing to lipid metabolism abnormalities": "",
  "Hypertension, high cholesterol, smoking, diabetes, obesity, and family history": "",
  "CAD is a multifactorial disease with both modifiable risk factors (hypertension, high LDL cholesterol, smoking, diabetes, obesity, sedentary lifestyle) and non-modifiable risk factors (age, sex, family history), requiring comprehensive risk management.": "",
  "LDL cholesterol is called 'bad' cholesterol because:": "",
  "It destroys red blood cells": "",
  "High LDL deposits cholesterol in artery walls, contributing to plaque buildup": "",
  "It is produced only by eating saturated fat": "",
  "It removes cholesterol from arteries": "",
  "LDL (low-density lipoprotein) carries cholesterol from the liver to the tissues; elevated LDL promotes cholesterol deposition in the arterial intima, triggering an inflammatory response that leads to atherosclerotic plaque formation.": "",
  "HDL cholesterol is called 'good' cholesterol because:": "",
  "It deposits cholesterol in arterial walls by infiltrating the endothelium and contributing to fatty streak formation and plaque buildup": "",
  "It has no function in the body and is merely an incidental byproduct of hepatic lipoprotein metabolism with no physiological role": "",
  "It helps remove cholesterol from arteries and transport it back to the liver (reverse cholesterol transport)": "",
  "It increases blood clotting by stimulating platelet aggregation and activating the coagulation cascade at sites of vascular injury": "",
  "HDL (high-density lipoprotein) is cardioprotective because it picks up excess cholesterol from arterial walls and transports it back to the liver for excretion (reverse cholesterol transport), effectively reducing atherosclerotic plaque burden.": "",
  "Peripheral artery disease primarily causes:": "",
  "Headaches and blurred vision from cerebrovascular insufficiency and reduced retinal perfusion": "",
  "Arm swelling and numbness from compromised venous return and peripheral nerve compression": "",
  "Leg pain with walking (claudication) due to reduced arterial blood flow": "",
  "Chest pain at rest from coronary vasospasm reducing myocardial perfusion": "",
  "Peripheral artery disease involves atherosclerosis of the arteries supplying the extremities, most commonly the legs, causing intermittent claudication (cramping leg pain during walking) that resolves with rest because the narrowed arteries cannot meet increased oxygen demand.": "",
  "Cardiovascular disease is the _____ cause of death worldwide.": "",
  "Leading (number one)": "",
  "Tenth leading": "",
  "Fifth leading": "",
  "Least common": "",
  "Cardiovascular disease, including coronary artery disease, stroke, and heart failure, is the leading cause of death globally, accounting for approximately 17.9 million deaths per year according to the World Health Organization.": "",
  "What is valvular stenosis?": "",
  "A normal variation in valve size": "",
  "Complete absence of a heart valve": "",
  "A valve that leaks and allows blood to flow backward": "",
  "Narrowing of a heart valve opening that restricts blood flow through it": "",
  "Valvular stenosis occurs when a heart valve becomes stiffened, thickened, or calcified, narrowing the opening and restricting blood flow, which forces the upstream chamber to work harder to push blood through the constricted orifice.": "",
  "What is valvular regurgitation?": "",
  "A normal finding in healthy hearts": "",
  "Excessive calcium deposits on the valve": "",
  "A blocked valve that prevents all blood flow": "",
  "A leaking valve that allows blood to flow backward through it when closed": "",
  "Valvular regurgitation (insufficiency) occurs when a valve fails to close completely, allowing blood to leak backward; this reduces forward cardiac output and increases the workload on the affected chamber, potentially leading to heart failure.": "",
  "What is an aortic aneurysm?": "",
  "A dangerous bulging of a weakened aortic wall that can rupture, causing life-threatening hemorrhage": "",
  "A narrowing of the aortic valve caused by calcific degeneration, restricting blood flow from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta": "",
  "A blood clot that forms within the aortic lumen, partially or completely obstructing blood flow and posing a risk of distal embolization": "",
  "A normal physiological widening of the aorta that occurs gradually with age due to elastic fiber degradation, requiring no intervention": "",
  "An aortic aneurysm is a pathological dilation of the aortic wall caused by degenerative weakening, and it poses a serious risk of rupture, especially when it exceeds 5.5 cm in the abdominal aorta, which would cause massive internal bleeding.": "",
  "What is cardiac catheterization?": "",
  "An ECG recording technique that uses surface electrodes to measure the electrical activity of the heart and detect rhythm abnormalities and ischemic changes": "",
  "A blood pressure measurement technique that uses an arterial catheter to provide continuous real-time monitoring of systolic and diastolic pressures in critically ill patients": "",
  "A procedure that threads a catheter through blood vessels to the heart to visualize blockages and allow interventions like angioplasty and stent placement": "",
  "A non-invasive ultrasound of the heart that uses sound waves to visualize chamber size, wall motion, valve function, and ejection fraction in real time": "",
  "Cardiac catheterization is both a diagnostic and therapeutic procedure where a thin catheter is inserted into a peripheral artery and guided to the heart to inject contrast dye for imaging coronary arteries and, if needed, perform balloon angioplasty and stent placement.": "",
  "What does 'statin drug' mean?": "",
  "A drug that increases heart rate": "",
  "A blood thinner that prevents clots": "",
  "A drug that lowers blood pressure by blocking calcium channels": "",
  "A medication that inhibits HMG-CoA reductase to reduce LDL cholesterol production in the liver": "",
  "Statins are a class of drugs that inhibit the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase in the liver, which is critical for cholesterol synthesis, thereby significantly lowering LDL cholesterol levels and reducing the risk of atherosclerotic cardiovascular events.": "",
  "What is a pacemaker (artificial)?": "",
  "An implanted electronic device that delivers electrical impulses to regulate heart rhythm, primarily used for bradycardia": "",
  "A surgical procedure to replace damaged or diseased heart valves with mechanical or bioprosthetic substitutes, restoring normal unidirectional blood flow": "",
  "A type of external defibrillator that delivers electrical shocks through chest wall electrodes to terminate life-threatening ventricular arrhythmias": "",
  "A medication that controls heart rhythm by modifying the electrical conduction properties of the myocardium through ion channel blockade or autonomic modulation": "",
  "An artificial pacemaker is a small battery-powered device implanted under the skin with leads attached to the heart that delivers precisely timed electrical impulses to maintain an adequate heart rate when the natural conduction system fails.": "",
  "What is myocardial ischemia?": "",
  "Death of heart muscle from prolonged blockage": "",
  "Inflammation of the pericardium": "",
  "Excessive blood supply to the heart": "",
  "Reduced blood flow to the heart muscle causing oxygen deprivation without immediate cell death": "",
  "Myocardial ischemia is a reversible condition in which reduced coronary blood flow deprives the heart muscle of adequate oxygen, causing chest pain (angina) but not permanent tissue death; if prolonged, ischemia progresses to infarction.": "",
  "What is reperfusion therapy?": "",
  "A type of heart transplant procedure in which the failing heart is replaced with a donor organ from a brain-dead patient to restore normal cardiac function": "",
  "A therapy that reduces blood volume through therapeutic phlebotomy or diuretic administration to decrease cardiac preload and relieve congestion symptoms": "",
  "Treatment to restore blood flow to ischemic tissue, including angioplasty/stenting or thrombolytic drugs to dissolve clots": "",
  "A therapy that permanently increases heart rate by implanting a device that continuously stimulates the sinoatrial node to maintain adequate cardiac output": "",
  "Reperfusion therapy aims to quickly restore blood flow to ischemic heart muscle during a myocardial infarction, either mechanically through percutaneous coronary intervention (angioplasty/stenting) or pharmacologically with thrombolytic drugs that dissolve the occluding clot.": "",
  "What does 'edema' mean in the context of heart failure?": "",
  "Increased blood cell production by the bone marrow in response to chronic hypoxia, resulting in polycythemia and elevated blood viscosity": "",
  "A heart rhythm abnormality characterized by irregular electrical impulses originating from the atria or ventricles, disrupting normal cardiac synchrony": "",
  "A type of blood clot that forms within the deep venous system of the lower extremities, posing a risk of pulmonary embolism if dislodged": "",
  "Swelling caused by excess fluid accumulating in tissues due to the heart's inability to pump blood effectively": "",
  "In heart failure, the weakened heart cannot adequately circulate blood, causing blood to back up and increase hydrostatic pressure in the capillaries, forcing fluid out into the surrounding tissues and causing swelling (edema), particularly in the ankles, legs, and lungs.": "",
  "What is coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG)?": "",
  "A medication that dissolves coronary artery plaque": "",
  "An open-heart surgery that uses a vessel graft to create a new pathway around blocked coronary arteries": "",
  "A type of heart transplant": "",
  "A catheter-based procedure to place a stent": "",
  "CABG is a major surgical procedure in which a healthy blood vessel (often from the leg or chest wall) is grafted to bypass a severely blocked coronary artery, restoring blood flow to the ischemic myocardium downstream of the blockage.": "",
  "A 62-year-old smoker with diabetes and hypertension suddenly develops crushing chest pain, sweating, and shortness of breath. Paramedics administer aspirin immediately. Why is aspirin given as a first-line treatment in a suspected MI?": "",
  "Aspirin lowers blood pressure rapidly by dilating peripheral arteries through direct smooth muscle relaxation, reducing afterload on the left ventricle": "",
  "Aspirin reduces chest pain by acting as a pure analgesic that blocks pain signals at the level of the central nervous system, without affecting the underlying cardiac pathology": "",
  "Aspirin inhibits platelet aggregation, helping to prevent the clot from growing larger and improving blood flow to the ischemic heart muscle": "",
  "Aspirin dissolves the existing blood clot by activating the fibrinolytic system and converting plasminogen to plasmin, which enzymatically breaks down the fibrin mesh": "",
  "Aspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase in platelets, preventing the formation of thromboxane A2 and reducing platelet aggregation; this limits the growth of the coronary thrombus and improves blood flow past the partially occluded artery.": "",
  "A 70-year-old woman with a history of heart failure wakes up at 3 AM gasping for air and must sit upright to breathe. This symptom is called paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea. What causes it?": "",
  "Anxiety causing hyperventilation during sleep that lowers arterial CO2 levels and produces respiratory alkalosis, leading to a subjective feeling of breathlessness": "",
  "When lying flat, fluid redistributes from the legs to the lungs, overwhelming the weakened left ventricle and causing pulmonary congestion": "",
  "A blood clot that traveled from the deep leg veins to the lungs during sleep, causing acute pulmonary embolism with sudden-onset dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain": "",
  "Obstructive sleep apnea blocking the upper airway during sleep, causing repeated episodes of hypoxia and arousal with gasping respirations": "",
  "In left-sided heart failure, lying flat causes redistribution of peripheral edema fluid back into the central circulation; the failing left ventricle cannot handle this increased venous return, causing blood to back up into the pulmonary vasculature and fluid to leak into the alveoli, producing acute dyspnea.": "",
  "A patient with severe aortic stenosis develops left ventricular hypertrophy visible on an echocardiogram. The cardiologist explains this is a compensatory response. Why does the left ventricle thicken in response to aortic stenosis?": "",
  "The ventricle thins out and dilates to increase volume": "",
  "The ventricle wall thickens because it must generate higher pressures to force blood through the narrowed aortic valve": "",
  "The ventricle enlarges to store more blood": "",
  "The coronary arteries expand to supply more blood": "",
  "With aortic stenosis, the left ventricle faces increased afterload because it must push blood through a narrowed valve; like any muscle that works against increased resistance, the ventricular wall undergoes concentric hypertrophy to generate the higher pressures needed.": "",
  "A 45-year-old patient has a total cholesterol of 280 mg/dL, LDL of 190 mg/dL, and HDL of 32 mg/dL. The physician prescribes a statin and lifestyle changes. Why is this lipid profile so concerning?": "",
  "The total cholesterol is normal but HDL is too high": "",
  "These values are ideal and no treatment is needed": "",
  "Very high LDL accelerates plaque formation while very low HDL means insufficient cholesterol removal from arteries, dramatically increasing CAD risk": "",
  "Only the total cholesterol matters, and 280 is borderline normal": "",
  "This patient has a highly atherogenic lipid profile: elevated LDL deposits excess cholesterol in arterial walls while low HDL provides inadequate reverse cholesterol transport; together, they dramatically accelerate atherosclerosis and increase the risk of MI and stroke.": "",
  "A 50-year-old man undergoes cardiac catheterization revealing a 95% blockage of his left main coronary artery. The cardiologist recommends CABG rather than a stent. Why would surgery be preferred over stenting for this particular blockage?": "",
  "CABG is always less invasive than percutaneous stenting because it uses smaller incisions and does not require opening the chest, making it safer for high-risk patients with multiple comorbidities": "",
  "Left main coronary artery blockage is particularly dangerous because it supplies most of the left ventricle; CABG provides more durable and complete revascularization for this high-risk location": "",
  "Stents cannot be placed in arteries larger than 3 mm in diameter because the expanded metal mesh would fail to achieve adequate wall apposition and would be prone to migration and embolization": "",
  "Stenting is never effective for any coronary artery blockages because the restenosis rate is nearly 100 percent within six months, regardless of drug-eluting or bare-metal stent design": "",
  "Left main coronary artery disease is considered the most critical location because it supplies the majority of the left ventricle; CABG is often preferred because it provides multiple bypass routes and has been shown to have better long-term outcomes than stenting for this severe, high-risk anatomy.": "",
  "An ER physician tells a heart failure patient that their legs are swollen because of right-sided heart failure. The patient asks why a weak right ventricle causes leg swelling rather than breathing problems. What is the correct explanation?": "",
  "Right-sided failure causes fluid to leak into the lungs because elevated right ventricular pressure is transmitted retrograde through the pulmonary veins into the pulmonary capillary bed": "",
  "When the right ventricle cannot pump blood forward effectively, blood backs up into the systemic venous circulation, increasing venous pressure and causing fluid to leak into tissues, especially the legs": "",
  "Right-sided failure only affects the brain, causing confusion and altered mental status because reduced cardiac output leads to inadequate cerebral perfusion without any peripheral effects": "",
  "Leg swelling is caused by blocked peripheral arteries rather than heart failure, because arterial occlusion prevents blood from leaving the legs and causes fluid to pool in the interstitial spaces": "",
  "In right-sided heart failure, the right ventricle cannot adequately pump blood to the lungs, so blood backs up into the systemic venous system; increased venous hydrostatic pressure forces fluid out of capillaries into the interstitial spaces, causing dependent edema in the legs, ankles, and abdomen.": "",
  "A 28-year-old woman presents with a new heart murmur after a recent strep throat infection. The physician suspects rheumatic heart disease. How does a strep infection lead to valve damage?": "",
  "The infection causes hypertension that damages the valves mechanically": "",
  "Strep bacteria directly infect and destroy the heart valves": "",
  "Antibodies against strep bacteria cross-react with heart valve tissue (molecular mimicry), causing autoimmune-mediated valve inflammation and damage": "",
  "Strep infection causes blood clots that block the coronary arteries": "",
  "Rheumatic heart disease occurs when antibodies produced against group A streptococcus antigens cross-react with similar proteins in heart valve tissue (molecular mimicry), triggering an autoimmune inflammatory response that damages and scars the valves, most commonly the mitral valve.": "",
  "A patient is diagnosed with a massive saddle pulmonary embolism after developing sudden severe shortness of breath and chest pain following a long flight. The physician explains this is a cardiovascular emergency. Why is a large pulmonary embolism life-threatening?": "",
  "It only causes mild coughing that resolves on its own as the body's fibrinolytic system gradually dissolves the clot, and no medical treatment is needed": "",
  "It blocks blood flow to the brain by lodging in a cerebral artery, causing an embolic stroke with sudden neurological deficits including hemiplegia and aphasia": "",
  "It blocks blood flow through the pulmonary arteries, preventing gas exchange and causing right heart failure from acute pressure overload": "",
  "It causes the aorta to rupture by lodging in the aortic wall and weakening the vessel lining, leading to acute aortic dissection and massive hemorrhage": "",
  "A massive pulmonary embolism obstructs blood flow through the pulmonary arteries, dramatically increasing pulmonary vascular resistance; the right ventricle acutely fails under this sudden pressure overload, cardiac output plummets, and without emergency treatment the patient can die within minutes.": "",
  "A patient's cardiologist explains that prevention of cardiovascular disease should start early in life. A 35-year-old patient with no current symptoms asks what specific lifestyle changes provide the greatest benefit. Which combination is most evidence-based?": "",
  "Only having annual physical exams without lifestyle changes": "",
  "Regular exercise, healthy diet, not smoking, maintaining healthy weight, and managing blood pressure and cholesterol": "",
  "Only taking supplements and vitamins": "",
  "Only avoiding stress completely": "",
  "The strongest evidence for cardiovascular disease prevention supports a comprehensive approach: 150+ minutes per week of moderate exercise, a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, and whole grains, smoking cessation, maintaining a healthy BMI, and controlling BP and cholesterol to optimal levels.": "",
  "A 55-year-old patient with a mechanical aortic valve replacement must take warfarin (a blood thinner) for the rest of their life. The patient asks why this is necessary. What is the primary reason?": "",
  "Warfarin helps the body accept the foreign valve material by modulating the immune response and preventing the formation of antibodies against the prosthetic surface": "",
  "Mechanical valve surfaces are thrombogenic, so anticoagulation is required to prevent blood clots from forming on the valve that could cause stroke or valve malfunction": "",
  "Warfarin prevents the mechanical valve from calcifying by inhibiting calcium-dependent enzymes that deposit hydroxyapatite crystals on the prosthetic valve leaflets": "",
  "Warfarin reduces the risk of bacterial infection on the valve by maintaining smooth laminar flow across the prosthetic surface and preventing biofilm formation": "",
  "Mechanical heart valves have artificial surfaces that activate the clotting cascade when blood contacts them; without lifelong anticoagulation, thrombi can form on the valve, potentially causing valve obstruction, systemic embolization, or stroke.": ""
}